The paper proposes a distributed approach for the PageRank algorithm, which involves communication and computation among web pages. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. Additionally, the paper focuses on reducing computation and communication loads, which could also place it in the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category. The use of aggregation techniques and analysis of convergence properties suggest that the paper could also belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-category. The paper also deals with large-scale Markov chains and multi-agent consensus, which could place it in the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. Finally, the use of numerical examples and analysis of error in rankings suggest that the paper could also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
